---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import { UnitConverterCalculator } from "../../components/calculators/UnitConverter";

const title = "Cloud Units Converter";
const description =
  "Convert cloud billing units like GB and GiB or Mbps and MB/s, then estimate monthly transfer from throughput, utilization, and schedule assumptions without mixing decimal and binary units.";
---
<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/calculators/unit-converter"
  intro="Cloud pricing and dashboards mix decimal and binary units. Convert common storage and bandwidth units, then compare baseline vs peak transfer estimates."
  examples={[
    "1,000 GB ~ 931.32 GiB.",
    "100 Mbps at 30% utilization over 24h/day ~ monthly transfer estimate (GB/month).",
    "Peak 200% scenario shows the spike in monthly transfer."
  ]}
  includes={[
    "GB to GiB and Mbps to MB/s conversions.",
    "Throughput to monthly transfer estimate for planning.",
    "Days/month input to align with billing cycles.",
    "Baseline vs peak scenario table for transfer spikes.",
  ]}
  excludes={[
    "Protocol overhead and peak/diurnal patterns (use scenarios).",
    "Provider-specific billing unit rounding rules.",
  ]}
  how={[
    "GB to GiB uses 1 GiB = 1.073741824 GB.",
    "Mbps to MB/s uses 8 bits = 1 byte.",
    "Monthly transfer estimate multiplies throughput by utilization and time.",
    "Use 30.4 days/month for an average month."
  ]}
  faqs={[
    {
      q: "Do providers bill GB or GiB?",
      a: "Many providers bill decimal GB/TB, while OS tools often show GiB/TiB. Always check the billing unit in documentation."
    },
    {
      q: "Is the monthly transfer estimate exact?",
      a: "No. It's a simplified estimate. Real workloads vary by peak/off-peak patterns and protocol overhead."
    }
  ]}
  lastUpdated="2026-02-07"
  related={[
    { href: "/guides/egress-costs", label: "Guide: egress costs" },
    { href: "/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator", label: "Egress cost" },
    { href: "/calculators/rps-to-monthly-requests-calculator", label: "RPS to monthly requests" },
  ]}
>
  <UnitConverterCalculator client:load />
  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Where unit mistakes distort cloud bills</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      This page is not just a convenience converter. It helps prevent the small unit mismatches that quietly break
      egress, storage, and request-based models before the pricing math even starts.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GB vs GiB</strong>: storage bills often use decimal units while system dashboards show binary units.</li>
      <li><strong>Mbps vs MB/s</strong>: throughput charts use bits while payload and transfer planning often need bytes.</li>
      <li><strong>Hours and utilization</strong>: monthly transfer estimates drift when teams start from peak throughput instead of sustained usage.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to convert throughput into monthly transfer</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      Throughput-based budgeting works only when you explicitly separate the sustained rate from the short-lived peak.
      This page gives you a quick bridge between those two views.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Start from average throughput, not the highest spike visible in a dashboard.</li>
      <li>Apply utilization and schedule assumptions that match the real service window.</li>
      <li>Keep bits and bytes explicit so the conversion does not silently drift by 8x.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>When the “average Mbps” shortcut fails</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Download-heavy releases and cache misses can make the peak month look nothing like baseline.</li>
      <li>Short business-hour workloads should not be modeled as 24x7 traffic.</li>
      <li>Switching between GB and GiB mid-estimate makes later storage and transfer lines impossible to reconcile.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Quick unit checklist before you trust the output</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Confirm whether dashboards report GB or GiB before converting.</li>
      <li>Use average throughput, not peak, when estimating monthly transfer.</li>
      <li>Match hours/day to real schedules (not always 24x7).</li>
      <li>Keep bits vs bytes explicit when converting Mbps to MB/s.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Scenario planning</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Scenario</th>
          <th>Mbps</th>
          <th>Utilization</th>
          <th>GB/month</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Baseline</td>
          <td>Average</td>
          <td>Typical</td>
          <td>Derived</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Peak</td>
          <td>High</td>
          <td>Same</td>
          <td>Higher</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:0">
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/">Guides</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/">All calculators</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/egress-costs/">Guide: egress costs</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator/">Egress cost</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/rps-to-monthly-requests-calculator/">RPS to monthly requests</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</CalculatorLayout>
